    weekTitle: "Faith That Conquers Fear",
    title: "Be Not Afraid of Sudden Fear",
    ref: "Proverbs 3:25",
    scripture: "Be not afraid of sudden fear, neither of the desolation of the wicked, when it cometh.",
    walk: `Friend, here the proverb addresses a particular kind of fear, sudden fear, the fear that strikes us unexpectedly, and tells us not to be afraid of it: *Be not afraid of sudden fear, neither of the desolation of the wicked, when it cometh.* We are told not to be afraid of sudden fear. This teaches us, friend, that we need not be ruled even by sudden fear, the fear that strikes unexpectedly; for the one who trusts in the Lord, as the surrounding verses show, has a confidence that steadies him even against sudden fear.

Consider this particular fear: *sudden fear.* The fear that strikes unexpectedly. The proverb speaks of sudden fear, friend, the fear that strikes us unexpectedly, without warning. This is a particular kind of fear, friend, the sudden alarm, the unexpected dread, the fear that seizes us all at once when trouble suddenly comes. We may be going along calmly, friend, when sudden fear strikes, an alarming thought, an unexpected danger, a sudden crisis. This sudden fear, friend, can be especially gripping, seizing us before we have time to prepare. And the proverb addresses this very fear, friend, telling us not to be afraid of it.

And see the command: *Be not afraid of sudden fear.* We are told not to be afraid of sudden fear. The proverb tells us, friend, not to be afraid of sudden fear, nor of the desolation of the wicked when it comes. We need not be ruled, friend, even by sudden fear, the fear that strikes unexpectedly. But how can we not be afraid of sudden fear, friend, which strikes before we can prepare? The answer lies in the surrounding verses, friend, which speak of trusting in the Lord, of the Lord being our confidence. The one who trusts in the Lord, friend, who has the Lord as his confidence, has a steadiness that holds even when sudden fear strikes.

And see the ground of this steadiness, friend. The proverb here is part of a passage about trusting in the Lord and finding Him to be our confidence. The verse just after this one says that the Lord shall be our confidence and shall keep our foot from being taken. So the one who trusts in the Lord, friend, who has the Lord as his confidence, can be unafraid even of sudden fear; for his confidence is in the Lord, who keeps him. When sudden fear strikes, friend, the one whose confidence is in the Lord is steadied, for he knows the Lord is his confidence, keeping him. The Lord, friend, is the steadiness that holds us even against sudden fear.

So do not be ruled even by sudden fear, friend; for the one who trusts in the Lord has a confidence that steadies him even against the fear that strikes unexpectedly. Sudden fear can be especially gripping, friend, seizing us before we have time to prepare, an alarming thought, an unexpected danger, a sudden crisis. But you need not be ruled even by this sudden fear, friend. For if your confidence is in the Lord, friend, you have a steadiness that holds even when sudden fear strikes; for the Lord is your confidence, keeping you. So when sudden fear strikes, friend, rather than being swept away by it, return to your confidence in the Lord, who keeps you. Let your trust in the Lord, friend, be the steadiness that holds you even against sudden fear. For the proverb tells us not to be afraid of sudden fear, grounding this in our confidence in the Lord. So make the Lord your confidence, friend, that you might not be ruled even by sudden fear, but steadied by the Lord who keeps you.`,
    prayer: `Lord, thank You that I need not be ruled even by sudden fear, the fear that strikes unexpectedly, for the one who trusts in You has a confidence that steadies him. Sudden fear can be especially gripping, seizing me before I have time to prepare, an alarming thought, an unexpected danger, a sudden crisis. But thank You that I need not be ruled even by this sudden fear. For if my confidence is in You, I have a steadiness that holds even when sudden fear strikes, for You are my confidence, keeping me. So when sudden fear strikes, help me, rather than being swept away by it, to return to my confidence in You, who keep me. Let my trust in You be the steadiness that holds me even against sudden fear. So make Yourself my confidence, that I might not be ruled even by sudden fear, but steadied by You who keep me. In the name of Jesus Christ. Amen.`,
